---
import BaseLayout from '@/layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import Starfield from '@/components/Starfield.astro';
---

<BaseLayout
  active="about"
  title="Adamant — an introduction"
  description="An introduction to the Adamant protocol: its design constraints, its properties, and the people it is built for."
  ogImage="/about-og.png"
>
  <!-- ───────── HERO ───────── -->
  <section class="relative overflow-hidden pt-10 md:pt-16 pb-12 md:pb-16">
    <Starfield />
    <div class="pointer-events-none absolute inset-0 z-[1] glow-pulse" style="background:radial-gradient(ellipse 60% 50% at 30% 50%, rgba(255,125,77,0.08), transparent 65%)"></div>
    <div class="wrap relative z-[3]">
      <div data-reveal class="max-w-[1000px]">
        <span class="eyebrow"><span class="dot"></span>Introduction</span>
        <h1 class="mt-6 max-w-[14ch] font-display font-medium leading-[0.98] tracking-[-0.035em]" style="font-size:clamp(40px,5.6vw,84px)">
          <span class="block font-light text-ink-2">An introduction</span>
          <span class="font-bold text-ember">to the protocol.</span>
        </h1>
        <p class="mt-7 max-w-[46ch] text-[16.5px] leading-[1.7] text-ink-2">
          A Layer 1 with no foundation, no admin keys, and no upgrade authority after genesis.
        </p>
        <div class="mt-8 flex flex-wrap gap-3">
          <a href="/spec" class="btn-link solid">Read the specification <span class="arrow"></span></a>
          <a href="/genesis" class="btn-link">Genesis <span class="arrow"></span></a>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="mt-12 md:mt-16 pt-6 flex items-center justify-between border-t border-rule">
        <span class="font-mono text-[10.5px] tracking-[0.2em] text-ink-3">PRE-LAUNCH · SPECIFICATION · NO TOKEN</span>
        <span class="font-mono text-[10.5px] uppercase tracking-[0.2em] text-ink-2 hidden md:flex items-center gap-3">
          Continue
          <span class="inline-block h-px w-5 relative bg-ink-2 after:absolute after:right-0 after:-top-[3px] after:size-[6px] after:border-r after:border-b after:border-ink-2 after:rotate-[-45deg]"></span>
        </span>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ───────── §01 / FOUR PROPERTIES ───────── -->
  <section class="border-t border-rule">
    <div class="wrap">
      <div class="section-head">
        <div>
          <span class="num">§01 / CORE PROPERTIES</span>
          <h2><span class="light">Four properties</span>that constitute the protocol.</h2>
        </div>
        <p class="desc">Existing chains trade privacy, throughput, and governance neutrality against one another. The protocol is constructed on the premise that the trade-off is not fundamental — that integration of standard, peer-reviewed primitives delivers all three.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 gap-px bg-rule-2 border border-rule-2">
        {[
          {
            n: '01',
            wp: 'WP §1.1.7 · §11',
            title: 'No party can alter the protocol.',
            body: 'Most chains are governed by a foundation, multisig, or token-holder vote — entities with the technical capability to alter consensus rules, gas costs, or issuance schedules. Adamant adopts the Bitcoin posture: no on-chain governance, no admin key, no upgrade authority. Change requires a published spec, a public reference implementation, and a 2/3+1-by-stake supermajority of Node Runners (validators in the spec) each independently choosing to run new software.',
          },
          {
            n: '02',
            wp: 'WP §2.2 · §7',
            title: 'Privacy is the default.',
            body: 'On transparent chains, every transaction is publicly observable forever. When privacy is opt-in, using it becomes a signal. Adamant inverts this: sender, recipient, amount, and contract execution are encrypted by default, with selective disclosure available through view keys — a counterparty, a tax authority, an auditor — without exposing unrelated activity.',
          },
          {
            n: '03',
            wp: 'WP §2.4 · §8 · §10.4',
            title: 'Sub-second finality at design-N. Sub-cent fees.',
            body: 'Approximately 500 ms finality for owned-object transactions at the design-target validator count, with a per-transaction fee floor on the order of $0.0001 USD-equivalent. Throughput is a *floor*, not a cap: 50,000+ TPS on residential-fibre commodity hardware at the active-set ceiling of 75, with actual throughput routinely exceeding the floor when validators run better-than-baseline hardware. The floor is calibrated for broad participation rather than maximum headline figures, subject to empirical validation before genesis. Shielded transfers cost roughly one to two orders of magnitude more — still well inside consumer payment-network territory.',
          },
          {
            n: '04',
            wp: 'WP §2.3 · §8.5',
            title: 'Verifiable by anyone with a phone.',
            body: 'A Halo 2 recursive proof at every epoch boundary attests to the validity of all transactions and state transitions from genesis to the present. The proof is a constant-size artifact (≈5–10 KB) verifiable in 50–200 ms on a smartphone — anyone running the verifier becomes a Witness in the four-tier participation model (validators, provers, witnesses, service nodes). Proofs are produced by a permissionless prover market at steady state, with Node Runners falling back at degraded cadence so phone-verifiability never depends on the market materialising.',
          },
        ].map((p) => (
          <article class="bg-bg-2/70 backdrop-blur-sm p-7 md:p-9 flex flex-col gap-3.5 min-h-[320px] card-hover" data-reveal>
            <div class="flex items-baseline justify-between">
              <span class="font-mono text-[10px] uppercase tracking-[0.22em] text-ember">PROPERTY {p.n}</span>
              <span class="font-mono text-[10px] tracking-[0.18em] text-ink-4">{p.wp}</span>
            </div>
            <h3 class="font-display text-[22px] md:text-[26px] font-semibold leading-[1.15] tracking-[-0.025em]">{p.title}</h3>
            <p class="text-[14px] leading-[1.65] text-ink-2">{p.body}</p>
          </article>
        ))}
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ───────── §02 / DOWNSTREAM ───────── -->
  <section class="border-t border-rule">
    <div class="wrap">
      <div class="section-head">
        <div>
          <span class="num">§02 / DOWNSTREAM</span>
          <h2><span class="light">A permissionless market for</span>light-client infrastructure.</h2>
        </div>
        <p class="desc">Not a constitutional core property; a downstream consequence of the architecture. A chain that is permissionless at the participation layer, with standardised lightweight verification, naturally supports a market for the infrastructure that serves its lightweight clients.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 gap-px bg-rule-2 border border-rule-2">
        {[
          {
            tag: 'SERVICE NODES',
            wp: 'WP §9.10',
            title: 'Permissionless light-client infrastructure',
            body: 'A standardised query protocol opens a market for service nodes that wallets and applications query for state. No registry. No allocation. Anyone can run one. Wallets choose; payment channels settle. The chain remains correct without it — but its day-to-day usability stops depending on a few centralised RPC providers.',
          },
          {
            tag: 'VALIDATOR-FUNDED',
            wp: 'WP §10.5.5',
            title: 'Validators compete on service quality',
            body: 'Node Runners may, at their discretion, fund infrastructure providers from their commission revenue. The protocol does not allocate. It does not pick winners. Issuance still goes only to Node Runners. But Node Runners competing for delegators may choose to share revenue with the infrastructure that makes their delegators\' wallets fast.',
          },
        ].map((p) => (
          <article class="bg-bg-2/70 backdrop-blur-sm p-7 md:p-9 flex flex-col gap-3.5 min-h-[280px] card-hover" data-reveal>
            <div class="flex items-baseline justify-between">
              <span class="font-mono text-[10px] uppercase tracking-[0.22em] text-ember">{p.tag}</span>
              <span class="font-mono text-[10px] tracking-[0.18em] text-ink-4">{p.wp}</span>
            </div>
            <h3 class="font-display text-[22px] md:text-[26px] font-semibold leading-[1.15] tracking-[-0.025em]">{p.title}</h3>
            <p class="text-[14px] leading-[1.65] text-ink-2">{p.body}</p>
          </article>
        ))}
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ───────── §03 / FRAMINGS ───────── -->
  <section class="border-t border-rule">
    <div class="wrap">
      <div class="section-head">
        <div>
          <span class="num">§03 / FRAMINGS</span>
          <h2><span class="light">The protocol</span>in familiar terms.</h2>
        </div>
        <p class="desc">The protocol's relevance differs depending on the system it is compared to. The framings below describe what Adamant is in terms of infrastructure already familiar to particular audiences.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 lg:grid-cols-3 gap-px bg-rule-2 border border-rule-2">
        {[
          ['Compared to retail banking', 'A settlement layer with sub-second confirmation, sub-cent fees, default confidentiality, and no institution that can freeze accounts or alter the rules.'],
          ['Compared to international remittance', 'Half-second cross-border settlement at fraction-of-a-cent fees, twenty-four hours a day. No correspondent-bank intermediation. No holding period.'],
          ['Compared to Bitcoin', 'Bitcoin\'s design philosophy — credibly neutral, capture-resistant, settlement-grade — extended with programmable smart contracts, default privacy, and sub-second finality.'],
          ['Compared to typical crypto', 'No company. No investors. No allocation. No marketing fund. The protocol cannot pivot, run out of funding, or be acquired.'],
          ['Compared to transparent chains', 'On transparent chains, every transaction you have ever made is publicly observable forever. Adamant treats this as a structural defect, not a feature.'],
          ['From a settlement perspective', 'A settlement layer with cryptographic finality, sub-second confirmation, default confidentiality, and no counterparty risk on the issuer side. The issuer is mathematics.'],
        ].map(([t, p]) => (
          <article class="bg-bg-2/70 backdrop-blur-sm p-7 md:p-8 flex flex-col gap-3 min-h-[220px] card-hover" data-reveal>
            <span class="font-mono text-[10px] uppercase tracking-[0.22em] text-ember">{t}</span>
            <p class="font-display text-[17px] leading-[1.4] tracking-[-0.022em] font-medium text-ink mt-auto">{p}</p>
          </article>
        ))}
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ───────── §04 / DESIGNED FOR ───────── -->
  <section class="border-t border-rule">
    <div class="wrap">
      <div class="section-head">
        <div>
          <span class="num">§04 / INTENDED USERS</span>
          <h2><span class="light">The users for whom</span>existing chains are insufficient.</h2>
        </div>
        <p class="desc">If none of the following describes a meaningful concern, existing chains are likely adequate. Adamant is designed for users whose threat model includes their own bank, their own protocol foundation, or their own jurisdiction — and for applications whose correctness must outlive the institutions that hosted them at deployment.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 lg:grid-cols-3 gap-px bg-rule-2 border border-rule-2">
        {[
          { n: '01', tag: 'Privacy', t: 'Operating under restrictive financial controls', p: 'Privacy by default with selective disclosure permits compliance with legitimate legal obligations without surrendering one\'s complete financial history to all observers in perpetuity.' },
          { n: '02', tag: 'Settlement', t: 'Cross-border value transfer at consumer scale', p: 'Half-second settlement, fraction-of-a-cent fees, continuous availability, no correspondent-bank intermediation, no holiday or weekend gaps.' },
          { n: '03', tag: 'Permanence', t: 'Long-lived contractual arrangements', p: 'Wills, trusts, escrows, and inheritance instruments designed to outlive their creators by decades cannot rely on a foundation existing in 2070.' },
          { n: '04', tag: 'Custody', t: 'Self-custody outside the banking system', p: 'Banks fail; bank deposits depend on a government\'s solvency; bank accounts may be frozen. Self-custody on a chain that cannot be captured is a structurally distinct security model.' },
          { n: '05', tag: 'Apps', t: 'Building applications that hold value', p: 'Applications deployed on Adamant inherit its properties: default privacy, sub-cent fees, no platform owner with the capacity to ban a contract.' },
          { n: '06', tag: 'Sovereign', t: 'Public-record systems where the rules must hold', p: 'Voting registries, identity systems, public archives — applications for which "the rules cannot change without all participants agreeing" is the central security property.' },
        ].map((u) => (
          <article class="bg-bg-2/70 backdrop-blur-sm p-7 md:p-8 flex flex-col gap-3 min-h-[260px] card-hover" data-reveal>
            <div class="flex items-baseline justify-between">
              <span class="font-mono text-[10px] uppercase tracking-[0.22em] text-ember">{u.n} · {u.tag}</span>
            </div>
            <h3 class="font-display text-[18px] md:text-[20px] font-semibold leading-[1.2] tracking-[-0.02em]">{u.t}</h3>
            <p class="text-[13.5px] leading-[1.65] text-ink-2 mt-auto">{u.p}</p>
          </article>
        ))}
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ───────── §05 / WHAT IT IS NOT ───────── -->
  <section class="border-t border-rule">
    <div class="wrap">
      <div class="section-head">
        <div>
          <span class="num">§05 / WHAT IT IS NOT</span>
          <h2><span class="light">Notable absences,</span>by design.</h2>
        </div>
        <p class="desc">Most chain launches involve at least some of these. Adamant deliberately involves none. The absence is constitutive, not incidental.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 lg:grid-cols-4 gap-px bg-rule-2 border border-rule-2">
        {[
          ['A speculative investment vehicle', 'The protocol is not marketed as a path to financial returns.'],
          ['An ICO, airdrop, or token sale', 'No private round. No discount tier. No retroactive airdrop.'],
          ['Operated by a company or foundation', 'No legal entity owns or directs the protocol’s development.'],
          ['Funded by venture capital', 'No investors hold ADM. No allocation has ever been issued.'],
          ['A general-purpose-chain replacement', 'For users existing chains do not adequately serve.'],
          ['Subject to deposit insurance', 'Self-custody on a chain that cannot be captured.'],
          ['A finished implementation', 'A draft specification. Substantial work remains.'],
          ['A marketing programme', 'Public infrastructure. Treated as one.'],
        ].map(([t, p]) => (
          <article class="bg-bg-2/70 backdrop-blur-sm p-6 md:p-7 flex flex-col gap-2.5 min-h-[180px] card-hover" data-reveal>
            <span class="font-mono text-[14px] text-ember leading-none">×</span>
            <h4 class="font-display text-[16px] md:text-[17px] font-semibold leading-[1.25] tracking-[-0.02em]">{t}</h4>
            <p class="text-[12.5px] leading-[1.6] text-ink-3 mt-auto">{p}</p>
          </article>
        ))}
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ───────── §06 / GLOSSARY ───────── -->
  <section class="border-t border-rule">
    <div class="wrap">
      <div class="section-head">
        <div>
          <span class="num">§06 / GLOSSARY</span>
          <h2><span class="light">The protocol's</span>vocabulary, defined.</h2>
        </div>
        <p class="desc">Concise definitions of the terms used across this site, the whitepaper, and the reference implementation. The marketing site uses "Node Runners" as a friendly alias for validators; spec terminology (Witnesses, Provers, Service Nodes) is used directly for the other tiers.</p>
      </div>

      <dl class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 gap-px bg-rule-2 border border-rule-2">
        {[
          {
            term: 'Node Runner',
            spec: 'validator',
            def: 'A participant in the active set running DAG consensus and mempool decryption on residential-fibre commodity-desktop hardware. The active set is dynamic — a constitutional floor of 7 (the smallest size at which Byzantine fault tolerance retains margin against correlated failures) and a soft ceiling of 75 (calibrated to the throughput floor on residential fibre). Selection is first-come-first-served with persistent membership: validators are admitted in registration order and retain their slot continuously until they fail liveness duties or voluntarily unbond. Each publishes one vertex per 250 ms round, each referencing 2/3+1 of the prior round. Earns block rewards from the genesis pool, then post-launch issuance.',
          },
          {
            term: 'FCFS persistent membership',
            spec: 'WP §8.1.3',
            def: 'How Node Runners enter and leave the active set. When the count of registered, stake-eligible, online validators is at or below the ceiling (75), every such validator is in the active set; when it exceeds the ceiling, validators are admitted in *registration order* and the rest enter a standby queue. Slots are held continuously until liveness failure or voluntary unbonding; no forced rotation; no stake-weighted lottery. A small home-fibre validator who registered early and stays online cannot be displaced by a wealthier latecomer or a faster competitor. Delegation affects validator economics, not selection.',
          },
          {
            term: 'Witness',
            spec: 'WP §8.7.2',
            def: 'A phone-class participant in the four-tier model. Performs four roles: cryptographic attestation, data-availability sampling, recursive-proof verification, and fraud / reordering detection. Permissionless registration with a small Sybil-resistance stake (~100 ADM, 7-day unbonding); slashable for false attestations corroborated by other witnesses. Compensated from a slice of verification fees plus a small slice of issuance.',
          },
          {
            term: 'Prover',
            spec: 'WP §8.5.3',
            def: 'A GPU-class operator producing recursive Halo 2 proofs in a permissionless market. No stake, no application, no approval — provers race to submit valid proofs and win the per-proof bounty (the proof-generation fee dimension). Validators fall back to producing proofs at degraded cadence if the prover market is insufficient; phone-verifiability never depends on the market materialising.',
          },
          {
            term: 'Service Node',
            spec: 'WP §9.10',
            def: 'Permissionless light-client infrastructure provider. Wallets and applications query service nodes for state via a standardised query format. No registry; anyone can run one. Optionally funded by Node Runners from commission revenue (WP §10.5.5). Fee/ecosystem-funded; receives no issuance.',
          },
          {
            term: 'ADM',
            spec: 'native token',
            def: 'The protocol\'s native token. Native to the protocol layer (not contract-defined). 100M genesis pool drained over a five-year launch phase via burn-to-mint and Node Runner block rewards. Post-launch issuance: 4% → 1% per year, in perpetuity, distributed to Node Runners (majority) and Witnesses (small slice); provers and service nodes are fee-funded. Base fees burned via EIP-1559-style mechanism.',
          },
          {
            term: 'Genesis pool',
            spec: 'WP §10.2',
            def: 'A fixed 100,000,000 ADM that exists at the protocol layer, partitioned 70/30 between burn-to-mint claims and Node Runner block rewards. The pool is not held by any party; it is a counter that decrements only through public acquisition paths. Unclaimed tokens at year five are destroyed. The chain self-activates the moment 7 Node Runners are simultaneously registered, stake-eligible, and online — no recruited cohort, no human-in-the-loop activation.',
          },
          {
            term: 'Burn-to-mint',
            spec: 'WP §10.2.3',
            def: 'A genesis acquisition path. Anyone burns BTC or ETH at a verifiably unspendable address on the source chain; the protocol observes the burn via light-client verification of source-chain headers and mints the corresponding ADM at the protocol-defined rate. Per-address claim caps prevent early concentration.',
          },
          {
            term: 'Recursive ZK proof',
            spec: 'WP §8.5',
            def: 'A Halo 2 proof that attests to the validity of all transactions and state transitions from genesis to the present. Each new proof π_n verifies the prior proof π_{n−1} plus the current epoch\'s transactions, collapsing the entire chain history into a constant-size 5–10 KB artifact. Produced by the prover market at steady state with validator-fallback at degraded cadence.',
          },
          {
            term: 'DAG consensus',
            spec: 'WP §8',
            def: 'A directed-acyclic-graph consensus mechanism (Mysticeti-based). Node Runners produce vertices in parallel each round; ordering emerges from the structure rather than from a single leader. Commit waves finalise blocks every four rounds. At the constitutional floor (N=7–14) the chain halts on disagreement rather than forks — safety preserved at the cost of liveness during severe-unavailability periods.',
          },
          {
            term: 'Two-regime mempool',
            spec: 'WP §3.6, §3.8, §8.4',
            def: 'A mempool design that conceals transaction contents until ordering is committed. At N≥15, users encrypt to the upcoming epoch\'s BLS threshold key; 2/3+1 Node Runners publish decryption shares at the boundary (full MEV resistance). At N<15, users encrypt to a Wesolowski VDF puzzle; the rotated round anchor decrypts atomically with their vertex (bounded intra-anchor reordering surface, honestly disclosed). Hysteresis prevents flapping at the boundary.',
          },
          {
            term: 'Security tier',
            spec: 'WP §8.1.7',
            def: 'An on-chain signal indicating the chain\'s current scale, queryable as constant-time chain-state. Tier I (N=7–14): operational, time-lock encryption regime, suitable for ordinary transfers. Tier II (N=15–29): threshold-encryption regime active, suitable for moderate-value contracts. Tier III (N=30+): full design-target security. Wallets and applications adapt confirmation requirements accordingly.',
          },
          {
            term: 'Hybrid PQ posture',
            spec: 'Principle VIII, WP §2.8',
            def: 'Post-quantum security at the surfaces that matter most. ML-DSA (FIPS 204) for identity-binding operations: addresses, validator registrations, contract deployments, opt-in high-value transactions. ML-KEM-768 (FIPS 203) for key agreement underlying stealth addresses and encrypted memos — historical privacy survives the quantum threshold. Ed25519 by default for ordinary transactions (smaller signatures, lower bandwidth); the trade-off — that historical ordinary signatures are quantum-forgeable — is honestly disclosed rather than hidden.',
          },
          {
            term: 'Credible neutrality',
            spec: 'Principle I, WP §2.1',
            def: 'The property that no party — including the original implementers — possesses the unilateral capability to alter the protocol\'s operation. No on-chain governance, no admin keys, no upgrade authority, no premine. Enforced not by promises but by the structural absence of any mechanism to modify the protocol.',
          },
        ].map((g) => (
          <div class="bg-bg-2/70 backdrop-blur-sm p-7 md:p-9 flex flex-col gap-3 card-hover" data-reveal>
            <div class="flex items-baseline justify-between gap-3">
              <dt class="font-display text-[20px] md:text-[22px] font-semibold leading-[1.2] tracking-[-0.025em] text-ember">{g.term}</dt>
              <span class="font-mono text-[10px] tracking-[0.18em] text-ink-4 uppercase">{g.spec}</span>
            </div>
            <dd class="text-[14px] leading-[1.65] text-ink-2">{g.def}</dd>
          </div>
        ))}
      </dl>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ───────── CTA ───────── -->
  <section class="py-24 md:py-32 text-center border-t border-rule">
    <div class="wrap">
      <h2 class="mx-auto mb-8 max-w-[28ch] font-display font-medium leading-[1.05] tracking-[-0.035em]" style="font-size:clamp(28px,3.6vw,52px)">
        <span class="block font-light text-ink-2">For the full</span>protocol specification.
      </h2>
      <p class="mx-auto mb-10 max-w-[44ch] text-[15.5px] leading-[1.7] text-ink-2">
        Thirteen sections. Draft v0.1. Public for review.
      </p>
      <div class="flex flex-wrap justify-center gap-3">
        <a href="/spec" class="btn-link solid">Read the whitepaper <span class="arrow"></span></a>
        <a href="/genesis" class="btn-link">Genesis mechanism <span class="arrow"></span></a>
        <a href="/" class="btn-link">Home <span class="arrow"></span></a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
